Finals.

article.headline: Nolan's free throws lift Shock, force Game 3
article.linkText: Nolan's free throws lift Shock to win, force Game 3
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- Kedra Holland-Corn made Bill Laimbeer's preseason move look brilliant.

LIEBERMAN'S TAKE
This series would be over if it wasn't for Detroit's Kedra Holland-Corn. The Shock reserve scored a team-high 16 points, including a 3-pointer that cut L.A.'s lead to one to set up Deanna Nolan's heroic free throws.

Holland-Corn did a wonderful job of creating her own shots on Sunday, especially after Detroit's half-court offense broke down in the second half. She single-handedly carried this team and hit several big baskets when the clock was winding down and the Sparks were threatening.

The Shock did everything right in the first half, but they got a little bit tight in the half-court offense after the break and it nearly cost them. L.A. began hitting shots, got some momentum and eventually took the lead.

But one made shot from Ruth Riley might have prevented L.A.'s comeback. The Detroit center, who was 4 of 8 in the first half but finished 5-for-14, missed two open jumpers at the foul line she normally knocks down that could have stopped L.A.'s run much sooner. Instead, the Sparks kept hitting their shots and attacking the basket as the Shock started playing desperate.

Lisa Leslie was incredible in the second half, scoring 16 of her 18 points after the break. She was 0-for-5 in the first half but came out with an energy and fire in the second to finish 6-for-13, notching her 16th double-double of the season in front of a fantastic crowd that deserved the chance to watch Game 3.
-- ESPN analyst Nancy Lieberman

Holland-Corn scored 16 points, including 10 of Detroit's last 12, as the Shock beat the Los Angeles Sparks 62-61 on Sunday to force a decisive third game in the WNBA Finals.

Deanna Nolan's two free throws with 12.1 seconds left won the game for the Shock, but the victory would not have been possible without Holland-Corn's performance.

When the two-time defending champion Sparks made an 18-5 run to pull within two points with 8:13 left, Holland-Corn scored seven points in less than two minutes.

When Los Angeles took a 61-57 lead, Holland-Corn made a clutch 3-pointer with 1:11 left.

"When they went up four, all I heard was, 'Kedra, you're back in,' '' Holland-Corn said. "When I heard that, I said, 'If I get a shot, it's going up no matter what.'''

Having the confidence to take and make such a shot was what Laimbeer, the former player who is Detroit's coach and director of player personnel, was looking for when he traded the fifth pick in the draft to Sacramento for the fifth-year veteran in April.

Holland-Corn was a starter in Sacramento, but accepted her role as a reserve guard in Detroit.

"I'm very happy for her,'' Laimbeer said. "This was a great culmination of her season. We have one more game to go, but this just accentuated how professional she is.''

The best-of-three series will conclude Tuesday at The Palace, which drew a franchise-record crowd of 17,846 for Game 2. It was the second-largest crowd for a WNBA Final, behind the 19,563 for a 2000 game between New York and Houston at Madison Square Garden.

In June, Detroit rallied from a 16-point deficit to beat the Sparks in overtime and snap the longest winning streak in the seven-year history of the WNBA at 18 games.

"Again, it seems like we are just giving games away when we come in here,'' Los Angeles coach Michael Cooper said. "It was another game I thought we had in hand, we should have and we let Holland-Corn get loose for 3.

"That's the intestinal fortitude they have. They have been doing that all season long and again, they have come through with another one.''

BEATING THE ODDS
It usually doesn't work like this. Teams don't win games where they blow gigantic leads. What often happens is the lead starts to dwindle ... they start getting nervous, even though they shouldn't ... it slips away more ... they start freaking out ... they're suddenly behind ... they scramble helplessly ... they lose.

But on Sunday, Detroit survived the kind of game teams often don't survive, writes ESPN.com's Mechelle Voepel.

Detroit won a WNBA-best 25 games this season, one year after losing a league-worst 23 games.

It looked like their remarkable turnaround would end late against the Sparks when they led by four points with 1:28 to play after trailing by 19 late in the first half. But they couldn't make the shots or stops needed to win.

The Sparks were unable to get off a clean shot in the final seconds after DeLisha Milton tried to make a pass to Lisa Leslie near the basket.

Milton said there was contact, but it was a no-call situation. Leslie wasn't sure what happened.

"It's all a blur,'' Leslie said.

Detroit's top player, Swin Cash, was limited to nine points on 4-for-12 shooting. Nolan had 14 points.

Leslie scored 16 of her 18 points during Los Angeles' second-half comeback. Milton also scored 18. Nikki Teasley had 10 points and six assists.

Despite the loss, Cooper said it was "a great game,'' and showed the WNBA has gone to another level.

"For a minute, I thought I had a flashback,'' the former Los Angles Lakers guard said. "I thought I was in Boston Garden in '85 playing.''

Detroit's win was the first for the Eastern Conference in the finals since 1999 when New York beat Houston in Game 2.

Detroit overcame a disparity at the free throw line. The Sparks made 13 of 16 free throws and the Shock were 4-for-5.

The Shock, who never led during Game 1 in Los Angeles, scored 11 unanswered points to take a 24-9 lead midway through the first half and were ahead 38-22 at halftime.

Milton didn't recognize her team during the first half.

"It wasn't the L.A. Sparks that is known for winning championships,'' Milton said.
